english:
  title: A Memorial to Prime Minister Jeong
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The seasons have kept me from your august presence. Spring has passed, summer has faded, and now autumn deepens. I hear that you enjoy good health and prosperity—a source of great joy to me. When I served as an officer under your command, you showed me kindness beyond measure, despite my meager talents and limited abilities. I have never been able to repay even a fraction of your generosity.

    Moreover, having been deemed unworthy by the court and cast aside these ten years, how could I have dared hope to see my name recorded among the faithful and to take my place among the gentry? That I have been given this opportunity fills me with both gratitude and shame.

    The ancients say, "Prince and minister together make destiny." My fate rests entirely in your hands. Looking upon our realm, wherever your benevolence and authority extend, the Japanese invaders have fled far, and the people tend their fields in peace. Who but you has accomplished this? Though others credit you, I know you credit only His Majesty, never yourself. When you returned, the King honored you with high rank and appointed you Prime Minister, consulting you morning and night to broaden his vision. Surely the King has not disappointed you.

    Zhuge Liang received the deathbed command of Liu Bei and devoted himself faithfully to Liu Shan. Posterity has praised him for a thousand years. May you, like him, never falter in your duty. A scholar cannot help but speak earnestly for one who recognizes his worth—forgive me if my words seem bold.

    I have prepared detailed proposals on current matters, set down separately. If you find anything of merit, I humbly beseech you to consider them—it would bring great fortune to the realm.

    Regarding our naval forces: beyond our thirty-six old warships and cavalry, three provinces have constructed new vessels—thirty large ships requiring 150 men each, ten medium warships requiring 80 men each, and thirty scout ships requiring 50 men each. In total, we command 4,500 personnel. With such forces, how could we fail to conquer? This display of martial might is truly formidable.

    Yet recently, through requests and favors exchanged, names have been struck from our rosters while the ranks swell with weaklings. Some men have deserted; others have died of illness. We were fortunate that last year at Gangju the rebels scattered and dared not face us. But if the enemy learned of these gaps, and crisis suddenly struck, we could not summon land forces swiftly enough. Our victories have bred complacency—we cannot rely upon them. The strategy you spoke of at the wall was what the ancients called the inferior option.

    Recently, officers came by your command to inspect the troops. As names were called and the rosters checked, vacant positions were filled—weak men passed off as soldiers, and the inspectors noticed nothing. Cunning officials have long bent the rules to their advantage; this is no new vice. A mere deputy commander or judge cannot remedy such corruption. I propose that officers be dispatched to audit the cavalry registers, record discharges and replacements, fill gaps caused by desertion and death, and punish violations by military law. If this became standard practice each year, military orders would hold true, and the enemy would not dare probe for weakness.

    Consider, I beseech you—great fortune would attend such measures. When the Sui invaded Chen, Yang Su built massive warships named "Five Tusks," with five-story towers over a hundred feet high, carrying 800 men. Next came the "Yellow Dragon," holding 100 men, followed by smaller merchant vessels in descending size. Our great ships today are smaller than the Five Tusks; our medium warships are like the Yellow Dragons of old; our scout ships resemble those small merchant vessels, used merely for transport of provisions and supplies.

    When Wang Jun attacked Wu, he constructed even greater vessels—connected junks 120 paces long carrying over 2,000 men, larger still than the Five Tusks. Our nation now begins its preparation for naval warfare. Which vessel best serves this purpose remains uncertain to me. Yet by my reckoning, the advantage lies with the great ships. Yang Su himself commanded thousands of Yellow Dragons down the Wolf Tail Rapids; the Chen general Qu Xin was routed. When Lu Zhongsu held Jingmen, Su sent 1,000 men aboard four Five Tusks and destroyed a dozen enemy vessels, capturing 2,000 armored soldiers. Is this not clear proof? And consider our own victory at Gangju—outnumbered, yet we prevailed through the might of our great ships, as you yourself witnessed.

    Moreover, the Japanese ships do not match our medium warships in size. Smaller vessels carry fewer troops—how could they withstand our medium warships? As Mencius taught: the small cannot contend with the great, the few cannot withstand the many. Therefore, I propose we maintain and repair our great and medium warships to guard against unforeseen calamity. Our scout ships are already sufficient.

    Since the nation now focuses upon shipbuilding, I venture to offer this humble perspective. Should any merit be found here and even the smallest part be implemented, great would be the benefit to the realm.
  footnotes:
    - Zhuge Liang (諸葛武侯), known as Zhuge Kongming, was a legendary strategist of the Three Kingdoms period who served Liu Bei and faithfully supported his successor Liu Shan, becoming a model of loyalty for future generations.
    - The historical examples of Yang Su (楊素) and Wang Jun (王濬) were famous Sui dynasty military commanders known for innovative naval warfare tactics and ship construction.
    - The reference to 'long wall' (長城) strategy refers to a defensive rather than offensive posture, which Lee Cham critiques as inferior.
    - The Gangju (江州) campaign likely refers to a recent Korean victory against Japanese pirates or raids, demonstrating the effectiveness of larger warships.
